'''''Black Ice''''' is the sixteenth studio album by the Australian rock band [[AC/DC]]. It was produced by [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]] and released internationally on 17 October 2008. Guitarists [[Angus Young]] and [[Malcolm Young]] got together in London in 2003 to start composing tracks. Delays to its development occurred due to an injury to bass guitarist Cliff Williams and a change of labels from [[Atlantic Records]] to [[Sony Music]]. Recording occurred on March and April 2008 at [[The Warehouse Studio]] in Canada, the same studio as the band's previous album ''[[Stiff Upper Lip]]'', the eight-year gap between them is their longest between successive studio albums. O'Brien tried to recapture the rock sound of the band's early work, as opposed to the [[blues]] orientation of predecessors ''[[Ballbreaker]]'' and ''Stiff Upper Lip'', and made suggestions such as adding "[[soul music|soul]] [[Crooner|crooning]]" to [[Brian Johnson]]'s singing. ''Black Ice'' has the longest running time of any AC/DC studio effort.

''Black Ice'' was launched exclusively in physical formats, as the group does not sell its music digitally. [[Wal-Mart|Walmart]] got exclusive rights for the North American distribution, and was released along with an extensive marketing campaign which included displays focusing on AC/DC memorabilia. Three singles were issued, "[[Rock 'N Roll Train|Rock 'n' Roll Train]]", "[[Big Jack (song)|Big Jack]]" and "[[Anything Goes (AC/DC song)|Anything Goes]]". ''Black Ice'' went to number-one in 29 countries, including Australia, Canada, the United Kingdom, and the United States. It was the second best selling record of 2008, behind [[Coldplay]]'s ''[[Viva La Vida or Death and All His Friends]]'', and had shipped 6&nbsp;million copies worldwide by December. Critical reviews were generally positive, praising the music and resemblance to the classic AC/DC sound, although some critics found the work overly long and inconsistent. ''Black Ice'' was nominated for many awards, including the [[Grammy Award|Grammy]], [[Brit Award|Brit]], [[Juno Award|Juno]] and [[ARIA Music Awards|ARIA Music Award]]s; and was supported by a [[Black Ice World Tour|world tour]] between 2008 and 2010.

==Production==
''Black Ice'' marks AC/DC's sixteenth Australian issued studio album, and fifteenth internationally released. The band decided to take a break after finishing the [[Stiff Upper Lip World Tour]] in 2001, and resumed performing in 2003, with eight presentations that included AC/DC's induction in the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]], and opening three concerts for [[The Rolling Stones]]' [[A Bigger Bang Tour]].<ref>{{Cite book|pages=190-193|chapter=10: No Wuckin' Furries|title=AC/DC: High-Voltage Rock 'n' Roll: The Ultimate Illustrated History|first=Phil|last=Sutcliffe|publisher=Voyageur Press|location=Minneapolis, MN|year=2010|ISBN=0760338329}}</ref> During those two years, guitarists [[Angus Young]] and [[Malcolm Young]] wrote music separately, and then met in a London studio to work on new songs.<ref name=guitarworld>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.guitarworld.com/article/acdc_the_big_chill?page=0%2C1|page=2|title=AC/DC: The Big Chill|date=January 2009|first=Alan|last=di Perna|journal=[[Guitar World]]|publisher=[[Future US]]|ASIN=B001LNP3IO|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref>

The production of ''Black Ice'' was delayed for several reasons. AC/DC abandoned old label [[Atlantic Records]] to sign a deal with [[Sony Music]],<ref name="news.com.au"/> and changed labels within Sony, from [[Epic Records]] to [[Columbia Records]].<ref name=marshall/><ref name=nyt/> Bass guitarist [[Cliff Williams]] suffered an injury to his hand in 2005, and spent 18 months unable to play.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/news_press/access/1695839581.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Oct+10%2C+2008&author=CHARLES+RUNNELLS&pub=The+News+Press&edition=&startpage=G.12&desc=Local+bassist+back+in+%27Black%27+with+old+pals+from+AC%2FDC|title=Local bassist back in 'Black' with old pals from AC/DC |newspaper=[[The News-Press]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|author=Runnells, Charles|date=10 October 2008|accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> During the time Williams was recovering, the Young brothers perfected the songs they had written.<ref name=let>{{Cite news|archiveurl=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20090228181517/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/acdc/articles/story/22828684/let_there_be_rock_acdc_plan_big_comeback|title=Let There Be Rock: AC/DC Plan Big Comeback |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/acdc/articles/story/22828684/let_there_be_rock_acdc_plan_big_comeback|archivedate=28 February 2009|author=Hiatt, Brian|newspaper=Rolling Stone |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media LLC]]|date=18 September 2008|accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> Angus revealed that there was no pressure from Sony for the band to put out a new album, as the label was releasing DVDs and [[AC/DC remasters|remasters of the AC/DC catalogue]], and thus the group "could afford to sit back and say we<U+2019>ll do another album when we think we<U+2019>ve got all the goods."<ref name=guitarworld/> In a 2004 interview, vocalist [[Brian Johnson]] said that Angus had written harder riffs than those on ''Stiff Upper Lip''. Johnson also stated that would be writing song lyrics, for the first time since the band's 1988 album ''[[Blow Up Your Video]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal|title=AC/DC: Sympathy for the Rock|journal=[[Rock Hard (magazine)|Rock Hard]] Italia|publisher=Rock Hard Verlags|date=January 2004||language=Italian |last=Negonda |first=Marco}}</ref> but all tracks on ''Black Ice'' were credited to the Youngs.<ref name=allmusic.com/> On January 2006, Malcolm revealed in an interview that the band was working on a new album.<ref name=marshall>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.marshallamps.com/images/mars_law_issue_pdfs/ml%2009.pdf |title=AC/DC |accessdate= |last=Richardson |first=Joel |year=2006 |month=January |pages=14<U+2013>15 |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]] |journal=Marshall Law|publisher=[[Marshall Amplification|Marshall Publication]]|issue=9}}</ref>

When the Young brothers called Columbia Records' president [[Steve Barnett (music executive)|Steve Barnett]] to announce the making of a new album, Barnett recommended them producer [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]].<ref name=nyt>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/12/arts/music/12levi.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all|title=Ageless and Defiant, AC/DC Stays on Top Without Going Digital|author=Levine, Robert|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=8 October 2008|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> On 3 March 2008, recording started at [[The Warehouse Studio]] in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, the same studio where ''[[Stiff Upper Lip]]'' was made,<ref name=sos/> and lasted  for eight weeks.<ref name=brave/> Engineer [[Mike Fraser]], who has mixed all AC/DC albums since ''[[The Razors Edge (album)|The Razors Edge]]'', said they recorded in batches of three songs to "keep things interesting" and avert overextended sessions. According to Fraser, the band had not rehearsed the songs prior to entering the studio.<ref name=sos>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/jan09/articles/itfraser.htm|title=Secrets of the Mix Engineers: Mike Fraser|journal=[[Sound on Sound]]|publisher=SOS Publications Group|date=January 2009|author=[[Paul Tingen|Tingen, Paul]]|accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> Despite "a couple of tweaks in the writing, sparkling up the choruses a bit better" during the recording, the compositions were mostly complete.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/the_dirt/at_some_points_during_the/|title=
'At some points during the years I was wondering if there was ever going to be another AC/DC album'|author=[[Geoff Barton|Barton, Geoff]]|journal=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|date=14 Octover 2008|accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Still, the Young brothers had new ideas during production, including the song "[[Anything Goes (AC/DC song)|Anything Goes]]", written as studio sessions were nearly finished.<ref name=guitarworld4>di Perna, Alan (9 February 2009). p. 4</ref>

According to Angus, the title refers to gigs played during winter in the brothers' native country of Scotland. He said, "it rolled off the tongue" and it reminded him of "radio warnings up north of [[black ice]]."<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/music-news/2008/10/26/ice-memories-for-ac-dc-s-angus-young-78057-20839812/ |title=Ice memories for AC/DC's Angus Young - The Daily Record |newspaper=[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]]|editor=Sloan, Billy |date=26 October 2008|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> The band considered using the working title ''Runaway Train''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/5403-ac-dc-are-back-in-black-ice|title=AC/DC Are Back in Black Ice|first=Paul|last=Cashmere|publisher=Undercover News|date=2 July 2 July 2008|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref>

==Composition==
{{Quote box
| quote  = "The AC/DC music that I remember most is ''[[Highway to Hell]]'' and ''[[Back in Black]]'', which I view as pop songs done in a very heavy ferocious way. Angus and Malcolm were writing songs that had a lot of hooks and my only job was to make a record that made people say, <U+2018>I've missed AC/DC, and I<U+2019>m glad they<U+2019>re back.<U+2019>"
| source =&nbsp;<U+2014>Brendan O'Brien<ref name="nyt" />
| width  = 27%
| align  = right
| style = padding:8px;
}}
With ''Black Ice'', Brendan O'Brien tried to recapture the rock sound of their early work on albums such as ''[[Highway to Hell]]'' and ''[[Dirty Deeds Done Dirt Cheap]]''. He thought the two previous studio efforts, ''[[Ballbreaker]]'' and ''Stiff Upper Lip'', were more [[blues]]-based.<ref name=ap>{{Cite news|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/27572923/ns/today-entertainment/|title=AC/DC may finally get a little respect|date=6 November 2008|agency=[[The Associated Press]] |publisher=MSN|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> O'Brien encouraged the band to emphasise the "hooky, melodic side" of its song-writing, which Angus complimented, since he had "never been great with harmonies".<ref name=guitarworld3/> Mike Fraser declared the band aimed "towards ''The Razors Edge'' era, a little bit more up-tempo stuff."<ref name=brave/> O'Brien made suggestions about their performance, getting Angus to play [[slide guitar]] on "Stormy May Day",<ref name=guitarworld3>di Perna, Alan (January 2009). p. 3</ref> and telling Johnson to swap some screaming for a spot of "[[soul music|soul]] [[Crooner|crooning]]", as he was a soul singer and had to do what he needed to do. Johnson was worried that the rest of the band would think this did not suit their style of hard rock and roll, but the band was quite receptive.<ref name="news.com.au"/> The highly demanding singing style led to Johnson only recording his vocals for one hour a day.<ref name=let/> The rhythm section continues the basic structure from other AC/DC records, with Cliff Williams playing [[bassline]]s of [[eighth note]]s,<ref name=rs/> and [[Phil Rudd]]'s drumming being a consistent [[Time signature|4/4 time]], mostly on his [[snare drum|snare]], [[kick drum]] and [[hi-hat|hi-hat cymbal]]. Both musicians expressed contentment with their roles in the band; Rudd declared, "I'm not repressing skills. Most drummers are scared to try this", and Williams admitted he plays "the same thing in every song, for the most part", but added "[i]n AC/DC's music, the song is more important than any individual's bit in it".<ref>{{Cite news|archiveurl=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20090505231757/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/acdc_and_the_gospel_of_rock/page/3|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/acdc_and_the_gospel_of_rock/page/3|archivedate=5 May 2005|title=AC/DC and the Gospel of Rock & Roll|author=[[David Fricke|Fricke, David]]|newspaper=Rolling Stone|date=13 November 2008|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref>
{{Listen|filename=RockNRollTrain.ogg|title="Rock 'n' Roll Train" | description=Sample of the album's lead single, "[[Rock 'N Roll Train|Rock 'n' Roll Train]]". The song is centred around guitar riffs and elemental drum beats,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/turn_it_up/2008/10/acdc-recycles-c.html|title=Let there be rock! AC/DC recycles classic sound on 'Black Ice'|authorlink=Greg Kot|first=Greg|last=Kot|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=Tribune Company|date=16 October 2008|accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref> and features harmonic backing vocals during the chorus.<ref name=guitarworld/>|format=[[Ogg]]}}
Angus said that when composing with Malcolm they share ideas to make each track "work together" to form a complete album.<ref name=telegraph>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/3562134/ACDC-on-Black-Ice-We-stopped-developing-aged-17.html|title=AC/DC on Black Ice: We stopped developing aged 17|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|date=15 October 2008|author=Boyd, Brian|accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> With 15 songs which clock at over 55 minutes,<ref name=rs/> ''Black Ice'' has the longest running time of any AC/DC studio record.<ref name=monthly>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.themonthly.com.au/music-robert-forster-slippin-acdc-s-black-ice-1337|date=December 2008 - January 2009 |issue=41|title=Slippin<U+2019>: AC/DC<U+2019>s Black Ice|authorlink=Robert Forster (musician)|first=Robert|last=Forster|journal=[[The Monthly]]|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> Malcolm has declared that "about 60 or 70 song ideas" were developed,<ref name=brave>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/96233|title=Exclusive: Producer Mike Fraser Talks to BW&BK About New AC/DC Album - <U+201C>I Think It<U+2019>s Back More in The Direction of The Razor<U+2019>s Edge<U+201D>|last=Henderson|first=Tim|newspaper=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]]|publisher=The Perfect Page|date=5 September 2008|accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref> but Angus stated that most were discarded because of not being "representative of how we are".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/sftw/article1789897.ece|title=Interview with AC/DC |newspaper=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|first=Jaqui|last=Swift|date=10 October 2008|publisher=[[News International]]|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> Most of the album's tracks are about rock and roll itself <U+2013> Angus stated "Certain songs just seem to come to life when you add that phrase".<ref name=guitarworld4/> However, other themes served as inspiration. "[[Money Made]]" is a criticism on how, according to Angus, in the US "everything is money these days".<ref name=guitarworld4/> "War Machine" was based on a documentary on [[Hannibal Barca|Hannibal]], which led to the conclusion that the military has not changed since Ancient Rome.<ref name=motortrend>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.motortrend.com/features/consumer/112_0810_acdc_singer_brian_johnson_celeb_drive/printer_friendly.html|title=Celebrity Drive: AC/DC Singer Brian Johnson|date=October 2008|journal=[[Motor Trend]]|publisher=Source Interlink Media|first=K.S.|last=Wang|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=guitarworld5>di Perna, Alan (January 2009). p. 5</ref> "Wheels" tells about Johnson's passion for motorcars.<ref name=motortrend/> He described the release as the "best one we've done", he felt that while ''Back in Black'' was great for its time, ''Black Ice'' shows the band's "versatility".<ref name="news.com.au">{{Cite news| url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/music/acdc-reveal-black-ice-secrets/story-e6frexl9-1111117777168 | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|title=AC/DC reveal Black Ice secrets | first=Kathy | last=McCabe | date=17 October 2008|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref>

==Release and promotion==
On 15 August 2008, ''Black Ice'' was announced by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' as the title of the new AC/DC album, which would have a total of 15 songs.<ref name="Rolling Stones Smoking Section">{{Cite news |archiveurl=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20090512221900/http://rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/08/15/smoking-section-acdc-bob-dylan-the-stills|archivedate=15 August 2008|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/08/15/smoking-section-acdc-bob-dylan-the-stills/ |title=Smoking Section: AC/DC, Bob Dylan, The Stills |newspaper=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |accessdate=15 August 2008 |date=15 August 2008}}</ref> That same day, the band filmed the promotional video for its first single, "[[Rock 'N Roll Train|Rock 'n' Roll Train]]", in London.<ref name=train>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/listen-to-acdcs-new-single/story-e6freuy9-1111117327410|title=Listen to AC/DC's new single|first=Kathy|last=McCabe|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=News Limited|date=28 August 2008|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> Three days later, Columbia Records announced that ''Black Ice'' would be released on 20 October in the US, and made pre-orders available.<ref name="official confirmation">{{Cite press release|url=http://walmartstores.com/pressroom/news/8523.aspx |title=Black Ice set for release October&nbsp;20th |publisher=[[Walmart]] |accessdate=17 March 2011 |date=18 August 2008}}</ref><ref name="AC/DC Pre-Order Black Ice">{{Cite web |archiveurl=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20080821032339/http://acdc-preorder.shop.musictoday.com/Dept.aspx?cp=14359_14367|archivedate=21 August 2008|url=http://acdc-preorder.shop.musictoday.com/Dept.aspx?cp=14359_14367 |title=Pre-Order AC/DC's ''Black Ice''| publisher=AC/DC official website |accessdate=19 February 2011 |date=29 August 2008}}</ref> "Rock 'n' Roll Train", was issued on 28 August,<ref name=train/> with "[[Big Jack (song)|Big Jack]]" and "Anything Goes" following in some markets.<ref name=voltage211/> The track, "Spoilin' For a Fight", was used by the [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] as the theme song for its [[Survivor Series (2008)|2008 Survivor Series]] event,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/2008/exclusives/acdcdebut|title=AC/DC<U+2019>s <U+2018>Black Ice<U+2019> debuts at No. 1|date=1 November 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=19 March 2011}}</ref> and "War Machine" was later included in the [[Iron Man 2 (soundtrack)|soundtrack album]] for ''[[Iron Man 2]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sonymusic.co.uk/releases/1552/|publisher=Sony Music UK |title=AC/DC: ''Iron Man 2''|accessdate=18 March 2011}}</ref>

The CD version was also available in a hard-cover, deluxe edition with a 30-page booklet containing exclusive new illustrations, studio and live photographs of the group as well as lyrics to the songs.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/95881|title=AC/DC - Limited Edition-Deluxe Version of Black Ice Detailed|journal=Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles|publisher=The Perfect Page|date=1 September 2008|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> A limited edition steel-box version, containing the CD, a 20-page colour booklet, a DVD featuring the "Rock 'n' Roll Train" video and a [[making of]] documentary, a large AC/DC flag, five stickers and a [[Gibson]] guitar pick, was issued in Germany and the United Kingdom in December.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=111785|title=AC/DC's 'Black Ice' Was Australia's Third-Highest-Selling Album of 2008|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] ([[Roadrunner Records]])|date=2 January 2009|accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=ukbox/> It appeared as a vinyl LP on two 180-gram discs, in a heavy gate-fold package featuring the standard red lettering artwork on the front. The LP was sold through the official website and through independent record shops in the US.<ref name=vinyl>{{Cite web|url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/6405-ac-dc-black-ice-vinyl-goes-exclusive-to-indies |title=AC/DC Black Ice Vinyl Goes Exclusive To Indies |publisher=Undercover News|date=3 October 2008| first=Paul |last=Cashmere|accessdate=13 November 2010}}</ref>  An unknown number of copies of the vinyl version were incorrectly pressed, side 1B had tracks from [[The Clash]]'s ''[[Live At Shea Stadium]]'' instead.<ref name=voltage211>Sutcliffe, Phil (2010). p.211 "Selected Discography and More (Also Selective)"</ref> ''Black Ice'' was not issued digitally, as the band refuses to sell their tracks separately. Angus declared, "If we were on [[iTunes]], we know a certain percentage of people would only download two or three songs from the album - and we don't think that represents us musically."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/3561194/iTunes-under-threat-as-bands-take-their-business-elsewhere.html|title=iTunes under threat as bands take their business elsewhere|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|date=25 September 2008|author=Boyd, Brian|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> However, its entire content was leaked online two weeks early.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/technology/technology-news/new-acdc-album-leaked-online-20090616-cfvy.html|title=New AC/DC album leaked online|first=Asher|last=Moses|date=13 October 2008|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> Rumours spread that Sony Music tried to control leaks by releasing fake tracks on [[peer-to-peer]] websites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/6442-fake-ac-dc-files-flood-the-internet|title=Fake AC/DC Files Flood the Internet|publisher=Undercover News|first=Paul|last=Cashmere|date=8 October 2008|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref>

In North America, [[Wal-Mart|Walmart]] made a deal for the exclusive distribution of ''Black Ice'', though a few independent music shops managed to get copies by ordering them from foreign outlets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/6403-ac-dc-wal-mart-deal-gets-thunderstruck|title=AC/DC Wal-Mart Deal Gets Thunderstruck|publisher=Undercover News|first=Paul|last=Cashmere|date=2 October 2008|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> Angus declared that they picked Walmart since the company is the biggest physical music retailer in America, which they believed to be "the best alternative to iTunes".<ref name=telegraph/> The retailer created over 3000 "Rock Again AC/DC Stores" with displays showcasing albums, clothing, the ''[[No Bull]]'' DVD, the video game ''[[List of Rock Band track packs#AC/DC Live: Rock Band Track Pack|AC/DC Live: Rock Band]]'', and products from sponsors.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://books.google.com.br/books?id=OBQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26|title=Cold As 'Ice'|journal=Billboard|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|volume=120|issue=47|date=22 November 2008|author=Christman, Ed|page=26|accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=promo/> Gary Severson, a Walmart senior vice president, said that AC/DC was one of the rare artists whose loyal fan-base allowed to display other merchandise along with the music.<ref name=wsj>{{Cite journal |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB122939389438809445.html |title=At Best Buy, an Album Sounds a Sour Sales Note |author=Bustillo, Miguel; Smith, Ethan|date=16 December 2008|accessdate=19 February 2011|journal=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]}}</ref> In October, [[MTV]], Walmart and Columbia created "AC/DC Rock Band Stores" in cities without actual Walmart retail locations <U+2013> New York's [[Times Square]], and Los Angeles. "Black Ice" trucks were dispatched on their streets after the release, playing tracks and making stops each day to sell merchandise.<ref name=walmart>{{Cite web|url=http://walmartstores.com/pressroom/news/8686.aspx|title=AC/DC's Black Ice Rocks Into Walmart Nationwide Oct.&nbsp;20|publisher=[[Wal-Mart|Walmart]]|date=17 October 2008|accessdate=13 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=maaw/> Advertising agency [[Arnold Worldwide]] was awarded both Best Activity Generating Brand Volume by the Marketing Agencies Association,<ref name=maaw>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maaw.org/globesawards/pastwinners.aspx?id=1524&catid=24|title=The Globes Awards <U+2013> Past Winners <U+2013> 2009 <U+2013> Best Activity Generating Brand Volume|publisher=Marketing Agencies Association|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> and Best Retail/Co-Marketing Campaign by ''Promo Magazine'' for ''Black Ice''{{'}}s marketing campaign.<ref name=promo>{{Cite journal|url=http://promomagazine.com/pro_awards/acdc-album-launch/index.html|title=2009 PRO Awards: AC/DC Album Launch|date=4 August 2009|journal=Promo Magazine|publisher=Penton Media|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref>

==Packaging==
The cover of ''Black Ice'' was drawn by Joshua Marc Levy, art director for Columbia and a long time fan. In an interview with a fansite, Levy compared his enigmatic design to a road covered with [[black ice]], which is "not obvious to the driver" and takes a while to be understood.<ref name=highway/>There are four different covers, the standard edition with the red logo, the deluxe edition with a blue logo, and two variants to the regular design including using yellow or white-coloured logos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acdc.com/us/acdc-today/acdcs-black-ice-released-october-20th-2008|title=AC/DC's ''Black Ice'' Released October&nbsp;20th, 2008|publisher=AC/DC official website|accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> Many drawings were based on the working title ''Runaway Train'',<ref name=collector/> including the regular and the deluxe edition overall design resembling a train, "that travels around the world to spread the rock machine", according to Levy.<ref name=highway/> Levy worked on the cover while travelling with [[Pearl Jam]] on their [[Pearl Jam 2008 United States Tour|2008 tour]]. After doing the yellow version's artwork, Levy was requested to do two more in the same style, which became the red and white varieties. Then, during the promotional shoots, Levy made the deluxe edition art.<ref name=collector>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buoy.com/~bonfire/interviews.htm#levy|title=Interview with Joshua Levy|publisher=Highway to Hell|author=Voccia, Bill|date=3 June 2009|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> 

The centre of the standard, red logo artwork, has a watch behind the lightning of the AC/DC logo, representing a "temporal explosion", with the [[Tribal art|tribal motifs]] representing a special tribe, the AC/DC fandom. Wings form clouds above the watch to represent "eternal time". Angus appears atop the watch "controlling time" and on the sides wearing a [[straitjacket]] to "represent the folly of the group and the strength of his sound, this mix of guitars that makes you lose your footing". To fit the title ''Black Ice'', the image was printed with [[lacquer]] and [[varnish]] to give an ice-like quality, and the AC/DC logo is filled with photographs of [[ice crystals]].<ref name=highway>{{Cite web|url=http://www.highwaytoacdc.com/index.php?articleid=659|title=Interview de Joshua Marc Levy, auteur de la pochette de Black Ice|publisher=Highway to AC/DC|language=French|date=December 2009|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> The booklet and promotional photography were taken by music photographer [[Guido Karp]] (who toured with AC/DC during their Stiff Upper Lip World Tour),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guidokarp.com/files/Guido%20Karp%20Biography%20English.pdf|format=PDF|title=Biography|publisher=[[Guido Karp]]|accessdate=16 March 2011|quote=2001 tours: AC/DC Stiff Upper Lip world tour}}</ref> in August 2008 in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guidokarp.blogspot.com/2009/11/guido-karp-photo-shoot-with-acdc-london.html|title=Guido Karp photo shoot with AC/DC - London Aug 2008 |date=6 November 2009|publisher=Guido Karp|accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref>

