===Professional reviews===
Critical reviews of ''Black Ice'' were mostly positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/black-ice|title=Black Ice Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More|publisher=[[Metacritic]] (CBS Interactive)|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> Aaron Burgess of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' considered ''Black Ice'' the most inspired AC/DC album since ''The Razors Edge'', praising Brian Johnson's performance and saying the music sounds "harder, hungrier, and more relevant than anything on contemporary radio".<ref name=avclub>{{Cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/acdc-black-ice,6769/|title=''Black Ice''|first=Aaron|last=Burgess|work=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion|Onion.Inc]]|date=27 October 2008|accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]''{{'}}s Richard Bienstock complimented Brendan O'Brien's production, stating it restored a [[sonority]] closer to the [[Harry Vanda|Vanda]]-[[George Young (rock musician)|Young]] produced 1970s albums, as well as effective choruses like those with [[Robert John "Mutt" Lange|"Mutt" Lange]].<ref name=vv>{{Cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-10-22/music/the-new-ac-dc-record-passes-our-scientific-test|title=The New AC/DC Record Passes Our Scientific Test|first=Richard|last=Bienstock|date=22 October 2008|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|publisher=[[Village Voice Media]]|accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''{{'}}s reviewer David Marchese noted that while the music sounded the same as in other albums, the lyrical themes were darker and the band "reveals some new sonic tricks".<ref name=spin/> ''[[The Observer]]'' described ''Black Ice'' as "nearly ''Back in Black II''", praising the tight and "laid back" sonority and saying the band "can still teach the kids a thing or two about rock'n'roll".<ref name=omm>{{Cite news| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2008/oct/12/popandrock3 | location=London |newspaper=The Observer |location=UK | title=Rock review: AC/DC, ''Black Ice'' | date=12 October 2008| first=Peter | last=Kimpton|accessdate=17 March 2011|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]}}</ref>

However, some reviewers found it inconsistent, overly long or formulaic. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s reviewer Clark Collis complained that the songs were too similar, saying that "even 2000's fairly monochromatic ''Stiff Upper Lip'' had more varied material", and that the band's trademark groove "now seems in danger of becoming a rut".<ref name=ew>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20233197,00.html|title=Black Ice Music Review|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|author=Collis, Clark |accessdate=2 July 2009}}</ref> [[Allmusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] considered that after "Big Jack" the tracks went into a {{q|too-comfortable groove, fueled by too-tight rhythms and guitars that sound loud but not beefy}}, and agreed it was overly long, "stretching out to 15 tracks when [the album] should be no longer than ten."<ref name="allmusic.com">{{Cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=black-ice-r1442020/review|pure_url=yes}} |title= ''Black Ice'' - AC/DC |publisher=Allmusic ([[Rovi Corporation]])|date=20 October 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> Similarly, [[Robert Forster (musician)|Robert Forster]] of ''[[The Monthly]]'' praised the first four songs and the title track, but felt that "tracks five through 14 are tough going", with a "numbing predictability" and lacking the "hooks and originality good AC/DC songs have".<ref name=monthly/> David Hiatt of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' said that the Young brothers composed "tunes worthy of their musical muscle <U+2013> though not enough to fill an album", described Phil Rudd's performance as "inhumanly restrained", and considered that ''Black Ice'' "feels longer than its 55 minutes, thanks to a stretch of throwaway rockers".<ref name=rs>{{Cite news||url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/black-ice-20081030|title=Black Ice - AC/DC|newspaper=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |first=Brian|last=Hiatt|accessdate=2 July 2009}}</ref>

===Chart performance and sales===
''Black Ice'' made history debuting at number-one on album charts of 29 countries, and also has the distinction of being Columbia Records' biggest debut album since [[Nielsen SoundScan]] began tracking sales data for ''Billboard'' in March 1991.<ref name="29countries"/> It has been certified multi-platinum in fourteen countries, including the US, Australia, and Canada.<sup id="nbFoot01a" class="reference">[[#noteFoot01a|[A]]]</sup> Additionally, it has achieved platinum status in four countries, including the UK,<sup id="nbFoot02a" class="reference">[[#noteFoot02a|[B]]]</sup> and gold status in four other countries.<sup id="nbFoot03a" class="reference">[[#noteFoot03a|[C]]]</sup> ''Black Ice'' was the second best-selling album worldwide in 2008, behind only [[Coldplay]]'s ''[[Viva La Vida or Death and All His Friends]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/top50-2008.pdf|format=PDF|title=Top 50 Global Best Selling Albums for 2008|publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI)|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref> As of December 2008, it had shipped 6&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref name=wsj/>

On the first day of its US release (20 October), ''Black Ice'' sold upwards of 193,000 units.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Cohen, Jonathan|archiveurl=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20081118081814/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003876402|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003876402|archivedate=18 November 2008|title="AC/DC's 'Ice' Red Hot at Retail"|newspaper=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|date=22 October 2008|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> By 28 October, ''Black Ice'' debuted at number-one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart, selling over 784,000 copies in its first week, the second highest one-week sales of an album in the US of 2008, behind [[Lil Wayne]]'s ''[[Tha Carter III]]''.<ref name=billboard>{{Cite news |archiveurl=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20081029150910/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003878705|archivedate=18 November 2008|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003878705 |title=AC/DC Debuts at No. 1 With 784,000 |newspaper=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=28 October 2008|first=Keith|last=Caulfield |accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> It was AC/DC's second release to top the US charts, after their 1981's ''[[For Those About to Rock We Salute You]]'',<ref name=billboard/> and also became the biggest debut ever by a mainstream hard rock album.<ref name="yahoo26">{{Cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/18590/week-ending-oct-26-2008-headbangers-beat-out-high-schoolers/|title=Week Ending Oct.&nbsp;26, 2008: Headbangers Beat Out High-Schoolers|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|accessdate=3 November 2008}}</ref><ref name="29countries">{{Cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=107781 |title=AC/DC's 'Black Ice' Debuts at #1 in 29 Countries |publisher=Blabbermouth.net (Roadrunner Records)|date= |accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> As of 31 December 2008, the album has sold just 1.915&nbsp;million copies in the US, according to Nielsen SoundScan,<ref name=chartwatch>{{Cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/25945/chart-watch-extra-the-year-that-songs-overtook-albums/ |title=Chart Watch Extra: The Year That Songs Overtook Albums - Chart Watch |publisher=Yahoo! Music |date=31 December 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2011}}</ref> and was certified 2x Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref name=RIAA>{{Cite web| url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=Black%20Ice&artist=AC%20DC&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2009&sort=Artist&perPage=25| title=Gold and Platinum Database Search|publisher=Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA)|date=20 November 2008| accessdate=14 January 2010}}</ref> ''Black Ice'' also debuted at number-one on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Album Charts]], with over 90,000 units sold,<ref>{{Cite news | last = McCabe | first = Kathy | title = AC/DC's new album Black Ice No.1 in Australia and UK | newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group | date = 28 October 2008 | url =http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/music/acdcs-black-ice-no1/story-e6frexl9-1111117874079 | accessdate = 2 November 2008}}</ref> and the UK Album charts, with 110,000 copies sold.<ref name="eurobill">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/news/e3iadb60bbfae240bb7368c1402ba727c54|title=AC/DC's 'Black Ice' Dominates Euro Albums Chart|newspaper=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|author=Sexton, Paul|date=30 October 2008|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> It was their first chart topper in the UK since ''Back in Black'' (1980).<ref name=echo>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article5010109.ece|title=Echo of Eighties as AC/DC turn up the amps again|newspaper=The Sunday Times |location=UK|publisher=News International|first=Patrick|last=Foster|date=25 October 2008|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> In Germany, ''Black Ice'' became the 14th best-selling album of the 2000s, selling 1&nbsp;million copies and reaching 5<U+00D7> platinum.<ref name="musikindustrie.de">{{Cite web|url=http://www.musikindustrie.de/fileadmin/news/presse/100122_BVMI_Gold_Platin_01-12.09_FINAL.pdf|title=Gold- und Platin-Verleihungen 01.01. - 31.12.2009|language=German|date-22 January 2010|publisher=[[Bundesverband Musikindustrie]] (BVMI)|format=PDF|accessdate= 29, 2011}}</ref>

===Accolades===
In [[ARIA Music Awards of 2009|2009]], ''Black Ice'' won the [[ARIA Music Awards|ARIA Music Award]] for Best Rock Album and Highest Selling Album; they were nominated for Album of the Year and Group of the Year.<ref name="ARIANews">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-artist.php?letter=A&artist=AC/DC|title=History: Winners by Artist: AC/DC|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) |accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> It was nominated for Best International Album at both the [[Juno Award]]s and the [[Brit Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/theampersand/archive/2009/02/03/2009-juno-award-nominations-announced.aspx|title=The nominees for the 2009&nbsp;Juno Awards are...|newspaper=National Post |location=Canada |publisher=[[Postmedia Network]]|first=Veronica|last=Boodhan|date=3 February 2009|accessdate=3 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/uncategorized/acdc-iron-maiden-nominated-for-brit-awards/|title=AC/DC & Iron Maiden Nominated for Brit Awards|author=Bezer, Terry|date=21 January 2009|work=[[Metal Hammer]]|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|accessdate=3 March 2011}}</ref> Angus and Malcolm won the [[APRA Awards of 2010|APRA Award]] for Songwriters of the Year, and "Rock 'n' Roll Train" won Most Played Australian Work Overseas.<ref name="SongWin2010">{{Cite web | url = http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/apraawards/musicawards/history/2010Winners.aspx | title = 2010 Winners | publisher=[[Australasian Performing Right Association]] (APRA) | accessdate = 23 April 2010 }}</ref> At the [[Grammy Awards]], "Rock 'n' Roll Train" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]] in [[51st Grammy Awards|2009]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/awards/grammys/2008-12-03-grammy-nominations_N.htm |title=Nominations for the 51st Grammy Awards |editor=Jones, Brent|newspaper=USA Today |publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=2 April 2009 |accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref> while in [[52nd Grammy Awards|2010]], ''Black Ice'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]] and the track "War Machine" won the [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]] category.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/entertainment/article285687.ece/AC-DC-finally-win-a-Grammy|title=AC/DC finally win a Grammy|date=1 February 2010|agency=[[Reuters]] (Thomson Reuters)|newspaper=[[The Times (South Africa)|The Times]]|publisher=[[Avusa]]|accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref>

''Black Ice'' was ranked 41st on ''Rolling Stone'''s Top&nbsp;50 Albums of 2008 list,<ref>{{Cite news|archiveurl=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20090525090555/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/24958695/albums_of_the_year/26|archivedate=25 May 2009 |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/24958695/albums_of_the_year/26 |title=The 50 Best Albums of 2008 |newspaper=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|page=26|date=25 December 2008 |accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> 29th on a similar list by [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]],<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.qthemusic.com/cgi-bin/50bestalbums/track.pl?id=68|title=50 Best Albums <U+2013> ''Black Ice'' / AC/DC|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> 17th on ''[[Kerrang!]]''{{'}}s Top&nbsp;20 Albums of the Year,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Best Albums of the Year|journal=[[Kerrang!]]|issue=1241|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group|Bauer]]|date=20 December 2008}}</ref> and 3rd in [[UGO]]'s list of the 11 Best Albums of 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ugo.com/music/top-11-metal-albums-of-2008|title=Top 11 Metal Albums of 2008|publisher=[[UGO Networks]] ([[Hearst Corporation]])|first=Greg|last=Prato|date=11 December 2008|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref>

==Black Ice World Tour==
[[File:Madrid-acdc 20.JPG|thumb|right|AC/DC on-stage, Black Ice World Tour, [[Madrid]], Spain, 5 June 2009.|alt=Distant shot of a concert stage. An arch with spotlights stands above a life-size locomotive and two big screens which display the male singer in left profile. Below and in front of the locomotive is musical equipment and four band members. At extreme left is a male playing guitar he wears a school boy's uniform. Central stage has two guitarists with a drummer and his kit between them. Front stage has a catwalk with the singer turned to his left profile, he is cradling the microphone in his right hand and has his left fist near his face. He wears a cap, dark singlet and jeans.]]
{{main|Black Ice World Tour}}
To promote ''Black Ice'', AC/DC launched the [[Black Ice World Tour]] on 28 October 2008 in [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{Cite news|archiveurl=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20090116015316/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/09/11/acdc-announce-north-american-black-ice-tour-dates/|title=AC/DC Announce North American ''Black Ice'' Tour Dates|newspaper=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media LLC |first=Daniel|last=Kreps|archivedate=16 January 2009|date=18 September 2008|accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref> Two days earlier, they held a dress rehearsal in the same city. The tour lasted 168 shows through 11 legs, with the last in [[Bilbao]], Spain on 28 June 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acdc.com/us/acdc-today/black-ice-world-tour|title=Black Ice World Tour|publisher=AC/DC.com|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref>

The stage was designed by [[Mark Fisher]], who had worked on the Stiff Upper Lip World Tour. Inspired by the working title ''Runaway Train'' and the track "Rock 'n' Roll Train", the stage had a life-sized [[locomotive]], weighing 3500&nbsp;kg, as its centrepiece.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://livedesignonline.com/stagingrental/for_those_about_to_rock_0109/index.html|title=For Those About To Rock|date=27 January 2009|first=Marian|last=Sandberg|journal=Live Design Magazine|accessdate=17 March 2011|publisher=Penton Media}}</ref> Five songs from ''Black Ice'' were included on the tour<U+2019>s [[set list]], "Rock 'n' Roll Train", "Big Jack", "Black Ice", "War Machine", and "Anything Goes".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stufish.com/ac-dc/black-ice/press-and-credits-3.html|title=AC/DC at Allstate Arena: The perfect antidote for the daily grind|first=Greg|last=Kot|newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=31 October 2008|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref>

The Black Ice World Tour is AC/DC's most successful to date, grossing $441.6&nbsp;million, making it the [[List of highest-grossing concert tours|third highest-grossing concert tour of all-time]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=143523|title=AC/DC's 'Black Ice Tour' Is Second-Highest-Grossing Concert Tour in History|date=26 July 2010|publisher=Blabbermouth.net (Roadrunner Records)|accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref> Three concerts in December 2009 at the [[River Plate Stadium]] in [[Argentina]] will be released as the DVD ''[[Live at River Plate]]'' on 10 May 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acdc.com/us/news/acdc-live-river-plate-available-may-10th|title=AC/DC Live at River Plate Available May&nbsp;10th! | publisher=The Official AC/DC Site|date=8 March 2011|accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref> A limited edition [[coffee table book|photo book]] on the tour, ''AC/DC Black Ice World Tour 2008-2010'', by Matteo Abruzzo, was published in Italy in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Black-World-2008-2010-Photo-Limited/dp/8890542608/|title=Ac/dc ACDC Black Ice World Tour 2008-2010 Live Photo Book (2 Years on the Road With...) Limited Edition (Hardcover)|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref>

